write out rememebr sin theta = -sin-theta

and the cos version

To remember the trigonometric identities for sine and cosine of negative angles, recall:

- \(\sin(-\theta) = -\sin(\theta)\)
- \(\cos(-\theta) = \cos(\theta)\)

These identities can be thought of in terms of the unit circle and symmetry. The sine function is odd, meaning it flips when reflecting across the y-axis (which is what happens when you negate the angle), and the cosine function is even, meaning it stays the same under this reflection.
